{"key":"post-12521738","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12521738</id>\n<content>Depending on the substrate, if you're holding it down under water, start with an hour and then on subsequent substrates, go up from there if necessary.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I only soak sawdust substrate blocks for an hour, even though stamets recommends 24 to 36 hours.&amp;nbsp; I've found by experience if you over-hydrate a substrate it performs poorly, so you're better off to get smaller fruits sooner and then re-soak, rather than risking over-hydration which leads to little or no fruits at all and green molds.&amp;nbsp; You can easily tell how much water has been absorbed by weighing the substrate before and after soaking.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>12521731</prev>\n<first>12521381</first>\n<last>12521738</last>\n<when>1273252995</when>\n<utime>05/07/10 08:23 PM</utime>\n</post>"}